The FFP introduced Michel Platini after being placed in the UEFA Director's seat in 2007.
A former French player believed that clubs that were in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements were ultimately cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP rules redirected their attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spent horrendous sums for players y to build a global brand - suddenly was not so advantageous.
