Patients will gain access to ‘transformative’ treatment to prevent HIV from September on the basis of a decision by the Supreme Court on the financing of NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) reported that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through health services to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to finance a probationary period after the Court of Appeal supported the Supreme Court decision of last year, stating that NHS had funds to pay for PREP despite a statement that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a ‘significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a ‘deciding moment'.
The sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to begin receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 full implementation will take place across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is a pre-sex HIV drug to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PREP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among patients at risk.
Injecting PREP before sex means that the patient's body contains enough specific drugs to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
The clinics shall identify eligible participants who will sign their consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also sign up at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program comes to taxpayers at £10 million, and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute drugs after obtaining an international public contract.
The test period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PREP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should be complemented and fully burdened by the ever-extensive and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than thirty years of effort to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, Managing Director of NAT (National Aids Trust), said: ‘We are witnessing a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is given correctly and patients at risk, it will offer the possibility of changing the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients who are at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to persuade a partner, leading to improvements in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, the executive director of Terrence Higgins Trust said: ‘The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests throughout the country; we must ensure that it is accessible to every patient.
We now have a PrEP test drug at our disposal, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Secretary of Health Sharon Hodgson said: ‘The beginning of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delay and delay by the government.
Evidence indicates how transformative this medicine can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and the cessation of transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Follow-up tests will take us one step closer to a full understanding of the PREP benefits.
