On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a flower jersey and the same flower headband - on a subject they had discussed many times before - "about experience with blacks".
"Do you remember how I taught you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" remembers the interview.
"Now we're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"There was no way I would take her with me," Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the culmination... that occurred in the past.
She must have known and seen it with her own eyes and grew up in it.
It needed to develop not only in activism and organization, but at the same time it needed to know the difference between the different layers of experience with black people and what we need to do to free ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own, she is no different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I were to protect her from this experience, I would only harm her."
Upon arriving in Ferguson, the first stop of the South Florissant Road was opposite the police department, which became the base of activists who expected the words of Officer Darren Wilson about his eventual participation in the incident.
Here Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing for the other food.
Together, they prepared food in bags and helped distribute it to Protestants.
A new type of activism was slowly born in Ferrell's eyes.
"My activism turned upside down after 9 August," Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis college, she was the president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. association and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, during the evening demonstration, Ferrell became acquainted with the later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan.
Folayan said that he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
But Ferrell wondered: “Do you work on a documentary or are you trying to find a story that can be used? ”
Such a type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often white people, who wanted to earn money on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an unquenched interview: “We have heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that. ”
Folayan has already established cooperation with co-director Damon Davis, who is a respected local artist who deals with the subject of prisoners on death row.
His participation in the project was also inteserrated by Ferrell and along with six other locals who were followed by the "Whose Streets" team in the years following Brown's assassination.
"In this document, no one speaks for us, but it is our statement," Davis said.
"This was important to me - how these people will be represented - because I will be represented in the same way."
While the aim of the document was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an effort to see that the movement "is not about the savior leader, but about the rapprochement of the community," Folayan said - it turned out to be the most open to participating in filmmaking.
The document “Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, for example, as she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face at the thought of the first moment when she saw the final version of the document.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and to humanize black people, I had to open up."
In addition, Ferrell's story highlights the role of an eccentric black woman in the wider aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created in response to the killing of teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 on the social media campaign below #BlackLivesMatter - call themselves weirdos.
"Black eccentric women in leading positions ultimately stand behind the preservation of the movement," Ferrell said, "because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the weight of these events."
Folayan agrees with this statement, adding that “the move is actually supported by black women and a large number of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that "this is not just an affirative matter" and Ferrell is not the main protagonist of the documentary because of her views.
"It was she who was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"that she found herself in the front lines is not a coincidence, because life on these intersections in the skin of a black weirdo woman is dangerous.
You can feel the surge of energy even in front of the screen."
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television station cameras cleared their positions, but heavy racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving two and a half years of probation for blocking the highway during demonstrations.
She described the social political atmosphere in the area she calls home as a "disorder."
Still, it does not cease its efforts, to which it has committed itself since it set off on the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
All we have to lose are our chains."
