A Becoming Resemblance: An artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery are placed several faces of different skin shades - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on the wires. Each one of them seems to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cable recorders on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2, bears the name A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, which combines her experience with technology, computer science and art, and Manning - a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence reduced Obama three days before his retirement from the post of President of the United States.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual comment on DNA subserviency - as well as many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since she was young about being considered a woman. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of twenty charges, including violations of six spy laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photographs were held by prison employees, and only one black-and-white low-quality photo, to which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig she is now associated.
In 2015, positive responses to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions continued to resonate.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They prepared an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to supplement the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of opening a new exhibition.
However, visitations and photography were not allowed, so they approached Chelsea asking if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Supressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, President Obama asked for Manning's release a few days after the comic was released, which was a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It is indeed interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people seeking to publish government information and transgender troops while trying to find new ways to instigate resentments in areas he should promote with his tweets.
In response to the question regarding this special timing Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything is happening for a reason".
Under the statement of the artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is dotted with her heart) after the end of "self-acting factionism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede of letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By classifying 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to a sophisticated scientific dictionary artist) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
"I hope that people will get away with it, that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg. Her 2007 work Spurious Memories on the topic of video is also available.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging into King Kong's way from United States Disiplinary Barracks Prison with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition personally - which was predicted in the comic book - but when she does, she will be welcomed in the center of the room with her masks, her own genomic forms, sorted as a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like crowds," Dewey-Hagborg said about portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of mass movement, which takes the form of Chelsea and frees her."
