"In the near future we will complete the WADA plan" - Vice-President of Russian Government Mutko
Vice-President of the Russian Government Vitala Mutko said it would not take long to implement the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria and the re-establishment of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
“A part of the criteria of the new plan has already been completed and RUSADA has already acquired the right to planning and testing in cooperation with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
In view of this, the WADA plan has been updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of the WADA plan to pass the Code - which describes the criteria for renewing the validity of the RUSADA - which was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutka, the code contains nothing that should concern Russia.
“Everything has been announced and everything will also be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
However, one of the above criteria calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation investigated by Richard McLaren about the alleged sponsorship of doping Russian athletes by the government.
On the subject, Mutko said: “We are conducting an investigation, as our anti-doping system obviously failed.
All measures have been taken.
However, there were no state programs in our country and we cannot confess to something that never existed."
Mutek's words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russian RSport Smirnov, Smirnov admitted the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, adding: “On many occasions, we have stated that the report contains controversial attitudes and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report without reservation," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADA of performing doping checks within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organization allowed planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) this June.
After visiting the Moscow headquarters of the organization in July, WADA CEO Olivier Niggli stated that RUSADA was "on the right track" to renew its validity.
