Startups to help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of satisfaction of her e-commerce startup staff, but she did not find an adequate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unprofitable, or even misleading.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the entire process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of the hair care company Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, who employs 75 people.
So she asked for outside help.
New human resources startups are constantly appearing in the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific intent to measure employees' duties, startups allow companies to vote quickly, target specific teams and demographic groups, also offers complete employee anonymity and a hotline for filing complaints, and in some cases also allows informants to bypass superiors and contact the director directly.
“There are instruments like Strava and Fitbit on the market that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the startup of Glint based in Reedwood City.
Errett stated that Glint made her more aware of what her employees were thinking and feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and the vote of specific teams, Glint offers a company temperature map and a brief overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low rating managers - which allows the user to work on the correction.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is thrown into scandals after a former employee posted a post on his blog describing the corporate environment and harassing employees who dare speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global sector of control, regulation and compliance by 2020 may exceed $18.8 billion.
The startup convercent of Denver, Colorado, which helps companies in preventing and detecting inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the Uber scandals.
Almost 600 convercent clients include Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
He also recently accepted Uber under his wing.
Like Glint, Convert allows companies to send customizable "bleak" surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved in the problem, the complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The Court of Public Opinions has authorised regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and executive director of the startup of Conversion.
If the company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behaviour - and if regulators do not intervene - it can face costly consequences due to customer boycott, staff exhaustion or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, uses the Convergence for more than a year to raise employees' awareness of corporate policies and procedures and ensure easy way to contact corporate management.
Earlier, if the employee wanted to report any problem, he had to trace a phone number or e-mail to the company's management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful resolution.
Often it was a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general representative of Ruby Tuesday, according to which previously there was no reliable way to track complaints from employees.
Now that the company is using the Convertent, rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never been reached before by managers, sitting in offices, for miles away to deal with complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"This is closer to a holistic, overall view of employees' experience," said Vitrano, who manages Ruby Tuesday's group overseeing risk management.
"We also protect shareholders from litigation by employees."
The companies ceased to take the ethics, values and participation of employees lightly in 2002 after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed after Enron's fall in the matter of abuse of employee ethics rights, Quinlan said.
But it was only when the social media “lighted on the whole thing,” that companies began to realize that in the online world they could not simply hide their skeletons in the closet.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and opportunity approved by courageous capital investors, which supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent raised $10 million in total from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually took away $47 million in capital.
Glint earned $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners and won $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
The increasing number of researches clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to perceive that they are accepted and appreciated and that they devote their time to a company that seeks a positive mission.
"If people are happy in their work, they perceive that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of society," said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Benefits of LinkedIn, which uses both Convergence and Glint.
Investors earn if companies thrive and companies prosper if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool emerges on the market to ensure the commitment and commitment of employees to the company, it is no wonder that a lot of investors will be found to support this effort.
According to experts on working culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that when a company applies for feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if the change does not occur quickly - in the worst case at all - it can cause disappointment and lack of interest for employees.
"As soon as you ask for 4,000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies that relied too much on the data itself.
“ Because once you don’t finish things, the employees begin to wonder, ‘ Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should I care?'"
Madison Reed, which now regularly conducts a survey among employees every month, is able to solve the problem within one day thanks to Glint, said Errett.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and communication quality, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to resolve the problem successfully.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important view of its employees and hopes to achieve high employment in the long term in a field known for frequent redundancies.
"If you do not seek to create a transparent working environment, employees will not believe you," added Vitrano.
“And once you start losing your employees, you lose your customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
