Creating a graphic novel: a story about A Castle in England
The small castle Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video of the Squeeze group, and Margaret Thatcher also found her refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
Scotney, however, witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot near the Bewl River in Kent, Britain, inspiring the curly Jamie Rhodes of York's county - known as a hobby in historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the handwriting of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me," Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
A graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who resided in the castle of Scotney from the Middle Ages until the Eduard period. Each story illustrates a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer, and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of inspired documents of the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by a thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
“This is his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those times you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love archives!"
For someone who is so fascinated with old papers, support from National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to reside in the castle almost as a dream. (To tell the truth, I have extended my stay a bit.").
Rhodes spent time exploring Victorian "new" castle, going through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of hyenas on the wall and bottles that have been dumped for centuries in the ditch.
He walked around the property and explored the ruins of the old castle, talked to gamekeepers, gardeners, and occasionally also artists who worked on illustrations of his book.
He was "drinking whiskey and writing" at night.
The intimate history of Scotney is relatively large unknown, as the National Trust organization did not gain access to documents until 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as when “the aristocratics of many centuries scatter their hands with the words, ‘Bring it into the attic'."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps depicting property: “You may think the land dispute is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch.
Stop it, people!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a stepping stone and sink deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
"I found a record of a 1380 castle riot called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected in the end."
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - such as The Priest, who tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about a 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who reportedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after revealing the coffin).
Rhodes’ favorite family is Darrell’s: “I was intrigued by the male race — the men of that time were always in debt and spent money on things they could not afford.
Various generations of the Darrell family dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake the heads of heirs."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes seeks further adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he sucked inspiration for his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was absorbed by nature.
For Scotney, however, this is a special place.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I said to myself, 'Now I'm going back to fucking real life'."
