Usually, patients are reminded not to eat meat and dairy to relieve symptoms, but researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps create immune cells that promote intestinal resistance.
The head of the study, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the degradation of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once a bowl of scales leans to the side of the inflammation, an inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of research, scientists found the presence of immune cells promoting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a connection between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan they had mice in their diet, the more they had these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if the same thing turns out to be true of man, then a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, as part of a study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of identical mice kept separate cells lacked.
It deduced that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of the mice were tested by DNA sorting method and researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells missing from the second group of mice.
The mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked intestinal microbiome - they did not develop this kind of immune cells - they were given L. reuteri - and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers grew L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immunity cells evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the fluid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri bacteria cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been detected in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
Cervantes-Barragan added: “Every one of us should probably pursue the development of these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
A potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population."
