White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to the occasion of the celebration of the U.S. manufacturing industry held last month came to $24,000 according to Navy records published by TIME weekly.
The Green White helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of the program of July 17 in the White House, which was a show of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials were inspecting a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was exhibited alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift trolley from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before landing a helicopter on South Lawn as part of a "exceptional" event, reports Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for administering the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," wrote HMX-1 commander in an e-mail to his superior, deputy commander of the Air Force the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 on the occasion of the show, the beginning of which is scheduled for 3:00 and will remain in place until the complete clean-up of the entire place scheduled between 18:00 and 21:00.
The e-mail further stated that if there is a delay in leaving the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the Working Time Regulation.
The original crew remained on site that evening along with the helicopter and along with them a unit of security personnel.
It was not apparent from the records - retrieved by the weekly TIME - that the second crew was eventually sent.
Hatch Act prevents state officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this Regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was okay," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander replied.
This show "Made in America" was marked by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the President advocated a health reform that went through the Senate and talked about trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of air transport vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
The presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential aircraft drove in the background during his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the show 'Made in America', which presented products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn area and practice eventual arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current crew training, said the state official.
The helicopter unit flew the same day as part of the "non-president support missions" for the next eleven hours.
The White House stated that no more props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
Spokesperson Sikorsky stated that the company was in no way involved in negotiations to expose the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep accounts of the budget for presidential flights and the exact cost of the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy's observations.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for the 2017 fiscal year, reimbursement of DoD expenditure for VH-3D amounts to $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operational costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"To report taxpayers' costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates shall include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs which are included in the annual costs."
According to the 2015 RAND study, reimbursement of DoD expenditure does not include personnel costs, but includes fuel, maintenance and contractual costs.
Back then, White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for show purposes.
"The Idea parade held this week is to introduce products produced in the USA," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defence of our state and that they provide jobs to hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities in which countless U.S. citizens are involved.
This fact is to be recalled."
It is unclear if Trump was also looking at a helicopter while on his way to South Lawn. The only thing to be certain is that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House Trump approached a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three of my own."
